LOCAL AND PROPORTIONAL TARIFF
CONTAINING
RULES AND REGULATIONS
GOVERNING
THE GATHERING AND TRANSPORTATION
OF CRUDE PETROLEUM
BY PIPELINE
The rules and regulations published herein apply only under tariffs making specific reference by F.E.R.C. number to this circular; such reference will include supplements hereto and successive issues hereof. Specific rules and regulations published in individual tariffs will take precedence over rules and regulations published herein.
[N] Filed in compliance with 18 CFR ? 341.5 (Cancellation of tariffs) [C] This is a baseline tariff filing in compliance with the Commission's Order on Electronic Tariff Filings in Order No. 714 issued September 19, 2008, 124 FERC ? 61,270 (2008). [C] RULES AND REGULATIONS
5
Definition of Terms
As used in these rules and regulations, the following terms have the following meanings: "Barrel" means forty-two (42) United States gallons. "Carrier" means and refers to Phillips Texas Pipeline Company, Ltd. "Crude Petroleum" means the direct liquid products of oil and gas wells and the indirect liquid products resulting from the operation of gasoline plants or gas recycling plants or mixtures of such products.
10
Minimum Tenders
Tenders for the transportation of any kind or mixture of such Crude Petroleum for which the Carrier has facilities for segregating and batching will be accepted under this tariff in quantities of not less that ten thousand (10,000) barrels from one Shipper consigned to one consignee and destination. Crude Petroleum so tendered to the Carrier for gathering and trunkline transportation will be received as currently available providing the total within a 30 day period is not less than ten thousand (10,000) barrels only if the Carrier's facilities and operating conditions permit. The Carrier will not be obligated to forward Crude Petroleum so tendered until it has received from one or more Shippers - to be delivered to a single destination in a common batch - a quantity aggregating not less than twenty-five thousand (25,000) barrels of the same quality or different qualities to be commingled - provided that the Shippers agree to said commingling.
15
Destination Facilities Required
The Carrier will receive each shipment of Crude Petroleum for transportation only when the Shipper or consignee has provided the necessary facilities to which Carrier is connected and has made necessary arrangements for promptly receiving the said Crude Petroleum at destination.
20
Storage Facilities
The Carrier will provide storage necessarily incident to transportation and only such storage.
25
Quality of Crude Petroleum
No Crude Petroleum will be accepted for transportation except good merchantable Crude Petroleum properly settled and free from water, sediment and other impurities. Carrier reserves the right to reject any and all tenders when the Reid vapor pressure exceeds that permitted by Carrier's facilities and operating conditions. Crude Petroleum will be accepted for transportation only on condition that it will be subject to such changes in gravity, quality or characteristics while in transit as may result from the mixture with other Crude Petroleum. The Carrier shall be under no obligation to make delivery of the identical Crude Petroleum received, but may make delivery out of its common stock.
30
Measuring Deductions and Temperature Corrections
Crude Petroleum tendered to Carrier for transportation shall be metered or gauged and tested by a representative of the Carrier prior to or at time of receipt from the Shipper. The Shipper shall have the privilege of being present or represented at metering or gauging and testing. If tank tables are used, quantities will be computed from correctly compiled tank tables showing one hundred (100) per cent of the full capacity of the tanks. Corrections will be made for temperature to the basis of sixty degrees (60?) Fahrenheit. Further deduction will be made for full amount of basic sediment, water and other impurities, as the centrifugal or other test may show. The net balance will be the amount of Crude Petroleum to be delivered by Carrier at destination.
35
Payment of Transportation and Other Charges
The Shipper shall be responsible for payment of transportation and all other charges applicable to the shipment, and if required, shall prepay such charges or furnish guaranty of payment satisfactory to the Carrier. The Carrier shall have a lien on all Crude Petroleum received for transportation to secure the payment of all charges, including demurrage, and may withhold delivery of Crude Petroleum until such charges are paid. Upon default in the payment of the charges of the Carrier when due, or even in the absence of unpaid charges when there shall be a failure to take Crude Petroleum at the point of destination and thereby relieve the storage and other facilities of the Carrier, Crude Petroleum may be sold by the Carrier or its representative at public auction at the office of the Carrier in Bartlesville, Oklahoma, after publication for five successive days of notice in a newspaper published in said city of the time and place of sale and the quantity of Crude Petroleum to be sold. The proceeds of sale shall be applied to the payment of the charges of the Carrier, if any, and the balance shall be held for whomsoever may be lawfully entitled thereto.
40
Oil Involved in Litigation, Etc.
The Carrier will have the right to reject any Crude Petroleum, when tendered for transportation, which may be involved in litigation, or the title of which may be in dispute, or which may be encumbered by lien or charge of any kind, and it may require of the Shipper satisfactory evidence of his perfect and unencumbered title or satisfactory indemnity bond to protect the Carrier.
For explanation of abbreviations and reference marks see page 3 herein.
2
[C] Item No.
[C] Subject
[C] RULES AND REGULATIONS
45
Duty of Carrier
The Carrier shall not be required to transport Crude Petroleum except with reasonable diligence, considering the quality of the Crude Petroleum, the distance of transportation, and other material elements; but the Carrier may at any time after receipt of a consignment of Crude Petroleum upon 24 hours' notice to the Shipper or consignee tender Crude Petroleum for delivery from its common stock at the point of destination at a rate not exceeding 20,000 barrels per day of 24 hours; and at the expiration of such notice, a demurrage charge shall accrue on Crude Petroleum of such consignment so tendered but remaining undelivered at the rate of one-tenth of one cent per barrel for each day of 24 hours or fractional part thereof.
50
Liability of Carrier
The Carrier, while in possession of any Crude Petroleum, will not be liable for any loss thereof or damage thereto caused by an act of God, public enemy, quarantine, the authority of law, strikes, riots or the act or default of the Shipper or consignee. In the event of loss of Crude Petroleum, the Shipper shall stand the loss in the same proportion as the amount of his tender bears to the whole amount of the consignment of which it is a part, and shall be entitled to receive only such portion of his tender as is left after deducting his due proportion of the loss, as above. If such loss occurs to Crude Petroleum in a segregated shipment, the Shipper and Consignee thereof shall bear the entire loss, damage or delay which occurs. Transportation charges will be assessed only on the quantity delivered.
55
Claims Time for Filing
Claims for any loss or damage to Crude Petroleum must be made in writing to the Carrier within nine (9) months after delivery of the property, or in case of failure to make delivery, then within nine (9) months after a reasonable time for delivery has elapsed; and suits shall be instituted against Carrier only within two (2) years and one (1) day from the day when notice in writing is given by the Carrier to the claimant that the Carrier has disallowed the claim or any part or parts thereof specified in the notice. Where claims are not filed or suits are not instituted thereon in accordance with the foregoing provisions, Carrier will not be liable and such claims will not be paid.
60
Pipeage Contracts
Separate pipeage contracts in accord with this tariff and these Rules and Regulations covering further details may be required by the Carrier before any duty of transportation shall arise.
65
Rates Applicable
Crude Petroleum received shall be subject to the rates in effect on date of receipt of the Crude Petroleum by originating Carrier for transportation.
70
Application of Rates
The rates published in tariffs making reference to this tariff apply from the established receiving stations of the Carrier to the established delivery stations of the Carrier at or near points named. From any point not named in tariffs making reference to this tariff which is intermediate to a point from which rates are published, through such unnamed point, apply from such unnamed point the rate from the next more distant point and apply the gathering charge at the next more distant point. when gathering service is performed at the intermediate point. To any point not named in tariffs making reference to this tariff which is intermediate to a point to which rates are published through such unnamed point, apply to such unnamed point the rate published therein to the next more distant point.
75
Proration of Pipeline Capacity
When there shall be tendered to the Carrier, for transportation, more Crude Petroleum than can be currently transported, the transportation furnished by the Carrier shall be apportioned among all Shippers in such quantities and at such times to the limit of capacity so as to avoid discrimination among Shippers. The Proration Policy for Phillips Texas Pipeline Company, Ltd. dated February 13, 2006 is available on request by calling the number or writing to the address under the "Compiled by" heading on the title page of this tariff.
